int sequence(int n) {
    if (n == 1) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 2 || n == 3) {
        return -1;
    } else {
        return sequence(n-1) + sequence(n-2) + sequence(n-3);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "The " << n << "th number in the sequence is: " << sequence(n) << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

In this program, we define a function `sequence` that takes an integer `n` as input and returns the nth number in the sequence. If `n` is 1, we return 0. If `n` is 2 or 3, we return -1. Otherwise, we recursively call the `sequence` function with `n-1`, `n-2`, and `n-3` as inputs and add the results to get the nth number in the sequence.

In the `main` function, we ask the user to enter the value of `n`, call the `sequence` function with `n` as input, and print the result.

